benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/phase - Retrieve phase for a given subscription and date

covered: Valid Request: Successful retrieval (TC01) verifies 200 and JSON Phase response and Content-Type.
Query Parameters: Multiple combinations of subscriptionId/requestedDate are exercised (TC01–TC08, TC14, TC15).
Error Handling: Invalid formats, missing params, non-existent subscription, out-of-range dates produce appropriate 4xx/404 responses (TC03, TC04, TC05, TC06, TC07, TC08).
Authentication/Authorization: Unauthorized access is tested (TC09) to validate 401 behavior.
Dependency/Server Errors: Service/unavailable dependency case is covered (TC10 -> 503).
Security: Injection attempt handling is included (TC11).
Edge Cases & Performance: Empty DB (TC12), large dataset performance (TC13), concurrency (TC16), extra params (TC14), and boundary date behavior (TC15) are present.
gaps: Pagination: No explicit tests for pagination or paged responses. (If the endpoint never returns collections this may be N/A — needs confirmation.)
Caching Behavior: No assertions about caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control, Last-Modified) or conditional GET behavior.
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests for rate limit responses (429) or behavior when many requests are sent rapidly; concurrency tests exist but do not validate throttling.
Schema-level validation: Tests assert "Phase object" presence but do not validate Phase fields, types, or required properties against the Phase definition.
Consistent Content-Type & Content Negotiation: Content-Type is checked in TC01 only; other scenarios do not assert response media type or behavior for unexpected Accept headers.
Authorization variants: No tests for 403 (forbidden) when token is valid but lacks required permissions/roles.
Error payload shape: Tests check for error messages/status codes but do not validate a consistent error response schema (fields like code, message, type).
Ambiguous acceptance behavior: TC02 allows "200 or default phase" but does not define expected deterministic behavior — test should assert the exact expected outcome per API contract.
recommendations: Add schema validation tests that assert the Phase object fields, types, and required properties match the API definition/documentation.
Add caching tests: verify presence and values of Cache-Control, ETag/Last-Modified headers and conditional GET behavior (If-None-Match / 304 responses) where applicable.
Add explicit rate-limiting/throttling tests that exercise rapid request bursts and assert 429 responses or documented throttling behavior; distinguish from generic concurrency/performance tests.
Clarify and tighten TC02: decide whether missing requestedDate should return a default phase or current effective phase and make the test assert that exact behavior.
Add tests for 403 forbidden cases (valid token but insufficient permissions) if the API enforces fine-grained permissions.
Expand Content-Type checks to all successful and error scenarios and add tests for Accept header handling (e.g., Accept: text/plain -> 406 or JSON fallback if supported).
Add error-schema tests to ensure consistent error payload structure (code, message, etc.) across 4xx/5xx responses.

If pagination is applicable, add pagination tests (page size, page number, limits, and navigation headers). If the endpoint never paginates, add a note in tests/documentation marking pagination as N/A.
For security, extend injection tests to other inputs and assert internal details are not leaked; include fuzzing or malformed long inputs for robustness.
